\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
1.
 Purpose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The purpose of this policy is to establish the Configuration Management Database (CMDB) as the authoritative record of configuration identity for all deployed IT assets within the Elko County Information Operations Department.
 This policy defines what constitutes a Configuration Item (CI),
 governs the creation,
 maintenance,
 and verification of CI records in the designated system of record (Redmine),
 and establishes the enforcement mechanism by which CI record accuracy is embedded into day-to-day operational work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A CI record is distinct from an asset record.
 A 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 asset record answers whether a physical asset exists,
 who owns it,
 where it is,
 and what its lifecycle status is.
 A 
\series bold
Policy 3.08
\series default
 CI record answers what that asset's current configuration identity is,
 what its operational relationships are,
 and whether its record is complete and current.
 Both records co-exist in Redmine and cross-reference each other via the Related Issues field,
 but they serve different governance purposes and neither substitutes for the other.
 An asset enters inventory under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 It becomes a CI under this policy at the time of deployment into the operational environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department treats CI record accuracy as an operational obligation,
 not an administrative one.
 A deployed asset with an incomplete or inaccurate CI record is not fully serviceable.
 This policy establishes the mechanisms by which that standard is maintained continuously.
\end_layout

